//axhob_operation
{rbtgo_ark_enshrine}

NOTE: This operation enshrines upstream base images into
{gar_service}
as content-addressed, human-readable anchors.
The
{rbtr_director}
submits a Cloud Build job that copies each declared
{rbrv_image_origin}
from its upstream registry to GAR using
the reliquary skopeo image
(`skopeo copy --all`), preserving the manifest list and all per-platform manifests for multi-platform images.
The locator results are returned via `buildStepOutputs` and
{rbrv_image_anchor}
is then written back to the vessel regime locally as a
{rbst_locator}.

NOTE: Slots whose
{rbrv_image_anchor}
is already populated are processed under skip-if-set semantics.
The Director HEAD-validates that the locator resolves in
{gar_service}
. On HEAD 200, the slot's
{rbrv_image_anchor}
is left intact and no Cloud Build copy occurs for that slot. On HEAD 404, behavior depends on
{rbrv_image_origin}
: if ORIGIN is populated, the
{rbrv_image_anchor}
is treated as a stale derived cache (depot rotated, or upstream digest moved since the prior enshrine) and the slot is reclassified to-enshrine — Cloud Build regenerates the locator from ORIGIN and the writeback step overwrites the stale value; if ORIGIN is empty, the locator was written by an upstream caller as a hallmark-pin and 404 is fatal (caller wrote an unresolvable locator).
This admits hallmark-base vessels: a vessel whose base image is an internal hallmark (e.g., the airgap-bottle building FROM the just-ordained forge) carries an
{rbrv_image_anchor}
of `{gar_hallmarks_namespace}/«HALLMARK»/«BASENAME»:«HALLMARK»` written by the orchestrating procedure (handbook step or onboarding-sequence fixture) before enshrine runs with ORIGIN empty; enshrine then verifies the hallmark is reachable rather than re-mirroring it.
A vessel whose every slot resolves to skip requires no Cloud Build submission — enshrine reduces to local HEAD validation.

NOTE: Enshrine is a pre-build preparation step.
It must be run before
{rbtgo_ark_conjure}
when anchored base images are desired.
Conjure works without anchors (passing ORIGIN through), but anchored images provide reproducibility and air-gap readiness.

NOTE: Enshrine runs on Cloud Build, not the Director's workstation.
No local skopeo installation is required.
The GCB step uses Mason SA ambient credentials via the metadata server for GAR writes.

The enshrine operation:

//axhopt_typed_parameter
{rbrv_sigil}
. *Validate Input Parameters*:
.. {rbbc_require}
vessel provided as first argument
.. {rbbc_require}
vessel declares at least one base-image slot — that is, at least one of slots 1-3 has either
{rbrv_image_origin}
or
{rbrv_image_anchor}
populated
.. {rbbc_require}
vessel mode is `conjure` (`RBRV_VESSEL_MODE`)
.. {rbbc_require}
reliquary tool images exist in GAR (HEAD check on `docker:latest` canary)

//axhos_step
. *Classify Slots*:
.. For each indexed slot (n = 1, 2, 3), branch on the (ORIGIN, ANCHOR) pair:
... If
{rbrv_image_anchor}
is set, HEAD-request the locator's `«PACKAGE-PATH»:«TAG»` manifest in
{gar_service}
:
.... HTTP 200 — classify as *skip*. The slot's
{rbrv_image_anchor}
is left intact; no Cloud Build copy is performed.
.... HTTP 404 with
{rbrv_image_origin}
populated — classify as *to-enshrine*. The
{rbrv_image_anchor}
is a stale derived cache; ORIGIN is passed to the Cloud Build step for inspect-and-copy and the writeback step overwrites the stale value with the freshly-computed locator.
.... HTTP 404 with
{rbrv_image_origin}
empty — fail with directive naming the unresolvable locator. The locator was written by an upstream caller (orchestration) as a hallmark-pin; with no ORIGIN there is no source from which to regenerate.
.... Any other HTTP status — fail.
... Otherwise, if
{rbrv_image_origin}
is set: classify as *to-enshrine*. ORIGIN is passed to the Cloud Build step for inspect-and-copy.
... Otherwise the slot is empty and is omitted from the build.
.. If every declared slot resolves to skip, skip the Cloud Build submission entirely — the operation reduces to local HEAD validation.

